            "text": "Here's a thinking process:\n\n1.  **Understand User Query:** The user is asking \"How can I maintain good kidney health?\" This is a general health advice question about preventive care for kidneys.\n\n2.  **Identify Key Areas of Kidney Health:**\n   - Hydration\n   - Diet/Nutrition\n   - Exercise/Physical Activity\n   - Blood Pressure & Blood Sugar Control\n   - Avoiding Nephrotoxins (certain medications, supplements, substances)\n   - Regular Health Screenings\n   - Smoking & Alcohol Moderation\n   - Weight Management\n\n3.  **Structure the Response:**\n   - Start with a clear, supportive opening\n   - Organize advice into logical categories\n   - Provide evidence-based, practical recommendations\n   - Include important caveats/disclaimers (consult healthcare provider, especially if pre-existing conditions exist)\n   - Keep it concise and actionable\n\n4.  **Draft - Section by Section:**\n   *(Hydration)* Drink adequate water daily. Amount varies by individual, but generally 6-8 glasses is a good baseline. Listen to thirst cues and monitor urine color (pale yellow is ideal).\n   \n   *(Diet)* Eat a balanced diet rich in fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins. Limit sodium (<2,300 mg/day, ideally lower if hypertensive), added sugars, and processed foods. Moderate protein intake unless advised otherwise. Consider plant-based proteins occasionally.\n   \n   *(Chronic Conditions Management)* Control blood pressure and blood sugar. Hypertension and diabetes are leading causes of kidney disease. Follow medical advice, take prescribed meds, monitor regularly.\n   \n   *(Exercise & Weight)* Maintain healthy weight through regular physical activity (150 mins/week moderate exercise). Reduces strain on kidneys and helps control BP/blood sugar.\n   \n   *(Medications & Substances)* Avoid NSAID overuse (ibuprofen, naproxen). Be cautious with herbal supplements (some contain heavy metals or nephrotoxins). Don\u2019t smoke. Limit alcohol. Always consult a doctor/pharmacist before starting new meds/supplements.\n   \n   *(Screenings)* Get regular check-ups, especially if over 40, diabetic, hypertensive, or have family history. Tests: eGFR, urine albumin-to-creatinine ratio, blood pressure checks.\n   \n   *(Disclaimer)* General advice; not a substitute for personalized medical guidance.\n\n5.  **Refine & Verify (Medical Accuracy Check):**\n   - Hydration: Evidence supports adequate fluid intake, but overhydration isn't beneficial. Pale yellow urine is a reasonable guideline.\n   - Diet: DASH diet, Mediterranean-style diets are kidney-friendly. Sodium <2,300 mg aligns with AHA/ACC guidelines. Protein moderation is relevant only in existing CKD, but general advice to avoid excessive red/processed meat is sound.\n   - BP/Blood Sugar: Strong evidence linking hypertension/diabetes to CKD. Target BP generally <130/80 per ACC/AHA and KDIGO.\n   - Exercise/Weight: WHO recommends 150 min/week. Helps metabolic health.\n   - Meds/Substances: NSAIDs can cause acute kidney injury or worsen CKD. Smoldering kidney damage from long-term use is well-documented. Herbal supplement risks are real (e.g., aristolochic acid). Smoking increases CKD progression risk.\n   - Screening: KDIGO recommends annual screening for high-risk groups. eGFR and UACR are standard.\n   - Disclaimer: Essential for AI medical advice.\n\n   All points are evidence-based and align with current guidelines (KDIGO, AHA, CDC, NIH).\n\n6.  **Structure for Readability:**\n   Use bullet points, clear headings, concise language. Add practical tips. End with strong recommendation to consult a healthcare provider.\n\n7.  **Final Output Generation:** (Mental review of the drafted response matches the refined version. I'll produce it now.) \n   - Check tone: Professional, supportive, non-prescriptive\n   - Check accuracy: Up-to-date guidelines referenced implicitly\n   - Check safety: Includes disclaimer, warns against self-diagnosis/treatment\n   - Check completeness: Covers all major modifiable factors\n   - Ready.\u2705\n</think>\n\nMaintaining good kidney health involves a combination of lifestyle habits, preventive screenings, and managing underlying health conditions. Here\u2019s an evidence-based overview of what you can do:\n\n### \ud83d\udca7 Stay Properly Hydrated\n- Aim for consistent fluid intake throughout the day. For most adults, this means ~6\u20138 glasses of water, though needs vary based on climate, activity level, and health status.\n- A simple guide: pale yellow urine usually indicates adequate hydration.\n- *Note:* If you have heart failure, advanced kidney disease, or are on fluid restrictions, follow your clinician\u2019s specific advice.\n\n### \ud83e\udd57 Eat a Kidney-Friendly Diet\n- Focus on whole, minimally processed foods: vegetables, fruits, whole grains, legumes, nuts, seeds, and lean proteins.\n- Limit sodium to \u22642,300 mg/day (ideally closer to 1,500 mg if you have high blood pressure).\n- Reduce added sugars, refined carbs, and heavily processed meats.\n- Keep protein intake at recommended levels (~0.8 g/kg body weight for average adults). Excess protein isn\u2019t harmful for healthy kidneys, but very high intakes can increase kidney workload.\n- Consider dietary patterns like the DASH or Mediterranean diet, which support both cardiovascular and kidney health.\n\n### \ud83e\ude7a Control Blood Pressure & Blood Sugar\n- Hypertension and diabetes are the top two causes of chronic kidney disease (CKD).\n- Keep blood pressure generally below 130/80 mmHg (or as targeted by your provider).\n- If prediabetic or diabetic, work closely with your healthcare team to keep blood glucose and A1C within goal ranges.\n\n### \ud83c\udfc3\u200d\u2642\ufe0f Move Regularly & Maintain a Healthy Weight\n- Aim for at least 150 minutes of moderate aerobic activity weekly (e.g., brisk walking, cycling) plus 2 days of strength training.\n- Maintaining a healthy weight reduces inflammation, improves insulin sensitivity, and lowers blood pressure\u2014all protective for kidneys.\n\n### \ud83d\udc8a Use Medications & Supplements Wisely\n- Avoid frequent or long-term use of NSAIDs (ibuprofen, naproxen) without medical guidance; they can reduce kidney blood flow and cause injury over time.\n- Be cautious with herbal supplements and detox products. Some contain heavy metals or compounds toxic to kidneys (e.g., aristolochic acid).\n- Always check with a doctor or pharmacist before starting new medications or supplements, especially if you have other health conditions.\n\n### \ud83d\udead Avoid Tobacco & Limit Alcohol\n- Smoking damages blood vessels, including those in the kidneys, and accelerates kidney function decline.\n- Limit alcohol to moderate levels (\u22641 drink/day for women, \u22642 for men) or less, as excessive intake raises blood pressure and contributes to metabolic strain.\n\n### \ud83d\udd0d Get Regular Preventive Screenings\n- Annual check-ups should include blood pressure monitoring and, for many adults over 40, basic kidney tests:\n  - **eGFR** (estimated glomerular filtration rate)\n  - **Urine albumin-to-creatinine ratio (UACR)**\n- Screen more frequently if you have diabetes, hypertension, cardiovascular disease, obesity, or a family history of kidney disease.\n\n### \u26a0\ufe0f Important Note\nThese are general preventive guidelines. Individual needs vary significantly based on age, genetics, existing conditions, and medications. If you have risk factors or notice symptoms like swelling, fatigue, changes in urination, or unexplained nausea, consult a healthcare professional promptly. Early detection and management can prevent or slow kidney damage.\n\nWould you like help interpreting lab values, understanding kidney-friendly meal planning, or identifying which supplements to avoid?",
