            "text": "Here's a thinking process:\n\n1.  **Understand User Query**: The user is asking about the symptoms of high blood pressure (hypertension).\n\n2.  **Identify Key Medical Facts**:\n   - High blood pressure is often called the \"silent killer\" because it typically has no obvious symptoms.\n   - Most people with hypertension feel perfectly fine until significant damage occurs.\n   - When symptoms do occur, they're usually only in severe cases (hypertensive crisis).\n   - Symptoms of hypertensive crisis can include: severe headaches, vision changes, chest pain, shortness of breath, nausea/vomiting, nosebleeds, confusion/anxiety, blood in urine.\n   - It's important to emphasize that absence of symptoms doesn't mean it's not present.\n   - Regular monitoring and medical consultation are crucial.\n\n3.  **Structure the Response**:\n   - Start with a clear, direct answer: High BP often has no symptoms.\n   - Explain why it's called the \"silent killer\".\n   - List symptoms that may appear in severe cases/hypertensive crisis.\n   - Clarify when to seek immediate medical attention.\n   - Provide practical advice (monitoring, consulting a doctor).\n   - Include standard medical disclaimer.\n\n4.  **Draft the Response (Mental Refinement)**:\n   High blood pressure (hypertension) is often called the \u201csilent killer\u201d because most people experience **no noticeable symptoms**, even when readings are dangerously high. Many individuals only discover they have hypertension during routine check-ups or after complications develop.\n\n   However, in cases of **severely elevated blood pressure** (known as a hypertensive crisis, typically \u2265180/120 mmHg), symptoms may include:\n   - Severe headaches\n   - Nosebleeds\n   - Shortness of breath\n   - Chest pain\n   - Vision changes (blurred or double vision)\n   - Nausea or vomiting\n   - Confusion or anxiety\n   - Blood in the urine\n   - Flushing or dizziness\n\n   \u26a0\ufe0f If you experience these symptoms alongside very high blood pressure readings, seek emergency medical care immediately, as this can indicate organ damage or a life-threatening condition.\n\n   Because symptoms are rarely reliable indicators, the best way to know your status is through regular blood pressure monitoring. If you're concerned about your cardiovascular health, consult a healthcare provider for proper screening and personalized guidance.\n\n   *Disclaimer: This information is for educational purposes and does not replace professional medical advice.*\n\n5.  **Check Against Medical Accuracy**:\n   - Accurate: Hypertension is usually asymptomatic.\n   - Accurate: Symptoms appear mainly in hypertensive crisis.\n   - Listed symptoms match clinical guidelines (ACC/AHA, Mayo Clinic, NHS, etc.).\n   - Emergency threshold (\u2265180/120) is correct per major guidelines.\n   - Clear disclaimer included.\n   - No diagnostic claims, just factual information.\n\n6.  **Final Output Generation**: (Matches the drafted response closely, ensuring clarity, accuracy, and appropriate medical caution.)\u2705\n</think>\n\nHigh blood pressure (hypertension) is commonly referred to as the **\"silent killer\"** because the vast majority of people experience **no noticeable symptoms**, even when their blood pressure is significantly elevated. Many individuals only discover they have hypertension during routine health screenings or after complications like heart disease, stroke, or kidney damage have developed.\n\n### \ud83e\ude7a When Symptoms Do Appear\nSymptoms typically only occur during a **hypertensive crisis** (blood pressure \u2265180/120 mmHg), which is a medical emergency. Possible signs include:\n- Severe headache\n- Nosebleeds\n- Shortness of breath\n- Chest pain\n- Blurred or double vision\n- Nausea or vomiting\n- Confusion, anxiety, or difficulty concentrating\n- Blood in the urine\n- Flushing or sudden dizziness\n\n\u26a0\ufe0f **Seek emergency care immediately** if you experience these symptoms alongside very high blood pressure readings, as they may signal acute organ damage or impending stroke/heart attack.\n\n### \ud83d\udd0d Important Notes\n- Feeling \"fine\" does **not** mean your blood pressure is normal.\n- Some people mistakenly attribute mild fatigue, occasional headaches, or ringing in the ears to high blood pressure, but these are not reliable indicators and are more commonly linked to other conditions.\n- The only accurate way to know your blood pressure is through proper measurement with a validated cuff device.\n\n### \u2705 Recommended Action\n- Check your blood pressure regularly, especially if you're over 40, have a family history, or carry risk factors (obesity, high-sodium diet, smoking, chronic stress, diabetes).\n- Consult a healthcare provider for personalized screening schedules, lifestyle guidance, or medication if needed.\n\n*Disclaimer: This information is for educational purposes and does not replace professional medical evaluation. Always consult a qualified healthcare provider for diagnosis and management.*",
